About the project

  1. Open Data
  2. Data Science
  3. Open Science

Each week the students will finish two course exercises and give feedback to a fellow student. The course utilizes R-language which will be learned in the weekly exercises done at https://www.datacamp.com/. # Reading data:
learning2014 <- read.table("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/learning2014.txt", sep=",", header=TRUE)

The data here describes results from a questionaire done to students on a course Johdatus yhteiskuntatilastotieteeseen, and combines the information with the background and exam points of each student. The questionaire aim to uncover effects of learning strategies, (i.e. deep, surface and strategic learning methods). Aspects covered in the questionaire were related to attitude towards statistics and the learning methods used as follows:

  • Deep learning aspects (Seeking Meaning, Relating Ideas, and Use of Evidence)
  • Surface learning aspects (Lack of Purpose, Unrelated Memorising, and Syllabus-boundness)
  • Strategic learning aspects (Organized Studying, and Time Management)

Let us try to model the data.

# A linear model
my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + age + gender, data = learning2014)

The residuals seem to be distributed somewhat equally around value 0 in the quantiles. The standard error for the intercept and attitude are aprox. one magnitude smaller than the estimate, their t-values are high and P-values are low (therefore the significance is good). Age and gender are not good explanatory variables to model the examination points. Therefore, let us remove those variables from the model. Now, the model says that if attitude increases by 1 unit, then the exam points increase by 3.5 points. The model can explain approx. 19 % of the variation in the modelled variable.

# Remodelling without age and gender as explanatory variables:
my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
# Summary of the model

Let us next turn to the graphical model validation. Our linear model assumes linear relationship between explanatory variable (attitude) and the modelled variable (examination points). The errors of the model are assumed to be normally distributed around zero and not correlated with each other. The normal Q-Q plot shows relatively good normal distribution of the residuals (only, the estimates with the lowest residuals are slightly too low). The residuals vs.fitted plot shows that exactness of the estimate does not depend on the amount of examination points. The residuals vs.leverage plot shows, that there are leverages of the individual points are low and that there are no evident trends visible.

# Plotting the graphical model validation images:

plot(my_model, which = c(1,2,5))

Logistic regression excercise

The data in this chapter is combined from two data-sets in a freely available zip file. The datafiles contain students family background and free time activity information as well as first, second and final grades in mathematics and portugese. List of the variable names will be available under this chapter. More information on the contents of the file can be found here. Variables school, sex, age, address, famsize, Pstatus, Medu, Fedu, Mjob, Fjob, reason, nursery,internet were used as identifiers for joining the data. Only the observations present in both datasets were accepted. The variables not used for joining the two data have been combined by averaging. Average of weekday and weekend alcohol consuption was produced into variable alc_use, and logical variable high_use is true for students with higher than 2 value in the alc_use.

Age (age) is definitely interesting variable concerning alchohol consumption. I imagine that very young students are less likely to consume high amounts of alcohol than older students. Sex of the student (sex) might show cultural influence. I imagine male students are more likely to consume high amounts of alcohol. I also assume that mothers job (Mjob) or fathers job (Fjob) in health care related sector will reduce changes for high alcohol consumption. I will now make a analysis data set containing these variables and the logical variable for high alcohol use (high_use) and explore the disributions of the chosen variables.

The boxplot shows slighly higher ages for the high alcohol consuming students, but the range of ages is maybe too narrow to notice a clear difference (I was expecting larger distribution of ages, and younger students might show this trend better). As expected, the male students use high amounts of alcohol almost twice as often as female students. According to the assumption, The students might use less alcohol if their fathers work in healtcare or teaching sector, or are home compared to students whose fathers work in servises or other sectors. Unexpectedly, the mothers job does not show similar trend. Instead, the children of mothers who stay at home might have slight tendency to consume more alcohol than other students. Let us make a logistic regression model out of the findings here. The variables describing parents work will be mutated to logical variables Mhome (mother at home) and Func (father has a uncommon work status among fathers) to allow meaningful use of the logistic regression model.

# Mutations of the data
analysis <- mutate(analysis, Func = (Fjob=="at_home"|Fjob=="health"|Fjob=="teacher") )
analysis <- mutate(analysis, Mhome = (Mjob=="at_home") )
str(analysis)
## 'data.frame':    382 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ age     : int  18 17 15 15 16 16 16 17 15 15 ...
##  $ sex     : Factor w/ 2 levels "F","M": 1 1 1 1 1 2 2 1 2 2 ...
##  $ Mjob    : Factor w/ 5 levels "at_home","health",..: 1 1 1 2 3 4 3 3 4 3 ...
##  $ Fjob    : Factor w/ 5 levels "at_home","health",..: 5 3 3 4 3 3 3 5 3 3 ...
##  $ high_use: logi  FALSE FALSE TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE ...
##  $ Func    : logi  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE ...
##  $ Mhome   : logi  TRUE TRUE TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE ...
# Modelling
model <- glm(high_use ~ age + sex + Mhome + Func, data = analysis, family = "binomial")
summary(model)

The residuals are not nicely centered around the median. Instead we see a close packing of the lower values and larger range in the higher values. This can be seen in the very low odds ratio of the intercept. The mothers may stay home at ease; the dummy variable Mhome is not meaningful for explanatory variable for the model. The male sex is the best explanatory variable for high alcohol consumption, although it has a high standard error (the confidence interwall does not cross 1:1 odds ratio for low/high consumption). Age and uncommon working status of the father have some potential to explain the alcohol consumption (they cross the 1:1 ratio, although barely). Age increases the likelihood of high consumption by changing the increasing the odds ratio 0.18 units/year and uncommon working status of the father degreases the likelihood of high consumption by reducing the odds ratio 0.64 (if true). The interpretation (if both factors would be meaningfull for the model) is that if Func is true, then the student has similar tendency to consume high amounts of alcohol than a student three years younger than him/herself.

Let us test the predictive power of the model.

probabilities <- predict(model, type = "response")
analysis <- mutate(analysis, probability = probabilities)
analysis <- mutate(analysis, prediction = probabilities>0.5)
table(high_use = analysis$high_use, prediction = analysis$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   266    4
##    TRUE    102   10
# initialize a plot of 'high_use' versus 'probability' in 'analysis'
g <- ggplot(analysis, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))

# define the geom as points and draw the plot
g + geom_point()

The model seems to be grossly biased into estimating students as low users of alcohol. Let us compute the total proportion of students inaccurately classified by model.

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = analysis$high_use, prob = analysis$probability)
## [1] 0.2774869

Here we notice, that on average the model errs approximately in every fourth student. That is quite close to the amount (one third) of the students who actually have high alcohol consumption. Let us compare the resutls of the model to quessing that i) all male students have high consumption and female students low consumption of alcohol, and ii) there are no students with high use of alcohol.

table(analysis$sex, analysis$high_use) %>% addmargins()
##      
##       FALSE TRUE Sum
##   F     157   41 198
##   M     113   71 184
##   Sum   270  112 382

The model gives 106, the males drink quess 154, and the the students do not drink quess 112 false answers out of 383 observations. Clearly, the model and the the students do not drink quess seem to be of similar accuracy.

Clustering and classification

This time we are going to use demonstrational Boston-dataset from MASS-library. The dataset has 506 observations on total of 14 variables, numeric and integral (below the structure and the dimensions of the data are explored). Description of the dataset may be found here or here. According to the links given, the set contains the following variables:

  • *CRIM - per capita crime rate by town
  • *ZN - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • *INDUS - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
  • *CHAS - Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • *NOX - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • *RM - average number of rooms per dwelling
  • *AGE - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
  • *DIS - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
  • *RAD - index of accessibility to radial highways
  • *TAX - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
  • *PTRATIO - pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • *B(LACK) - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
  • *LSTAT - % lower status of the population
  • *MEDV - Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

The graphical overview of the data and the summaries of the variables found in the data are provided below. The pairvise scatter plots and histograms show that the variables with bell shaped (or nearly bell shaped) distribution are the average number of rooms per dwellign rm and the median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s medv. This can be further confirmed from the summary of the varibles - the 1st and 3rd quartiles in these variables are almost equally apart from the median. Interestingly, the rm and medv have positive correlation, and are negatively correlated with the % lower status of the population lstat. The Charles River dummy variable chas has very little correlation with any other variables. The proportion of non-retail business acres per town indus and the nitric oxides concentration nox have quite strong positive correlation, and correlate with age, dis, rad and tax. Age is the only one to have negative correlation with the other variables mentioned.

Next, we will fit linear discriminant analysis on the train-set and plot the results (with arrow plot from http://stackoverflow.com/questions/17232251/how-can-i-plot-a-biplot-for-lda-in-r)

# LDA fit on train-set
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ . , data = train)

# arrow-function for the plotting
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric (for arrow plot)
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col=classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

Let us proceed to the bonus excercise. The idea is to cluster the scaled Boston data, and find the discriminating factors for the cluster using LDA. Acces to radial highways, nitric oxide concentration, and industrial environment are indicators of bad neighbourhoods, and together with full value property tax rate (per 10 000 $) discriminate one of the clusters. Room number, median price of owner occupied houses and proportion of residential land show good neighbourhoods and make another cluster. Age is the only variable that discroiminates especially towarsds the last (remaining) cluster. Could it be that some age group (old/young) tends to live yet in a very different environment? Maybe older couples tend to move once their offspring leave the house?

Dimensionality reduction techniques

The data originates from a open access webpage. The human developmental index (HDI) was created to access the developmental stage of countries using human reserves (skills etc.) rather than industrial output of the country as the measure of the developmental stage. There are also variants of this index available. Overview of the calculations for obtaining the indices may be found here.

Briefly, the aspects covered by HDI are

  • long and healthy life (life expectancy)
  • knowledge (through measured and expected years of education)
  • standard of living (GNI per capita)

Gender equality index utilizes

  • Maternar mortality ratio
  • Adolescent birth rate
  • Secondary education % in males and females separately
  • % of females and males in labour market
  • Proportion (%) of parliaments seats taken by females

Last week, we made modifications to the data. A meta file for the modified data is available here. This week, we will utilize 8 variables from the modified data, i.e.ratio of proportions of population (the ratio of female % to male %) having secondary education (Edu2.FM) and rate of participation in labour force (Labo.FM), expected years of schooling (Edu.Exp) and life (Life.Exp), gross national income (GNI), maternal mortality rate (Mat.Mor), adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth) and percent of parliament seats taken by females (Parli.F). Below the structure and the dimensions of the data are explored. The data now has 155 observations with data on all the 8 variables (observations with missing values were dropped out).

Let us try principal component analysis without standardizing the data first, and let us visualise the results using a biplot. Then let us perform the same operation on standardized data. The results show how the variable with largest variance in the unstandardized data (GNI) will be weighed over all the other variables of the unstandardized data. The standardized data show much more proader distribution of the observations on the scatter plot with two prinsipal components describing the highest amount of variance. There, Labor.FM and Parli.F seem somewhat correlated with principal component no:2 and all the other components show positive and negative correlation with principal component no:1. This was to be expected from the correlations we saw earlier while inspecting the data. Here the arrow sizes are the same (due to standardization of the data). I take the result to mean, that educating all kids will also lead to females going towards secondary education and not having babies as young, and increase the life expectancy maybe at least partly due to reduced maternal mortality.
